resources.string:
You can think of the audible beacon as a *"lighthouse for the ears"*, telling you where your destination lies relative to your location, as the crow flies. Like a lighthouse, it does not give you a route — you may need to make many navigation choices along the way, just as a sailboat makes several strategic *"tacks"* to get closer to a lighthouse. The continuous rhythmic sound of the audible beacon is spatialised from the direction of the destination and helps you stay aware of the destination’s location relative to you as you walk. When you are walking directly towards the destination, or you point the phone towards it, a higher‑pitched *"ring"* sound will be heard. This helps you pinpoint the destination’s direction because the rhythmic sound can sometimes be hard to perceive in noisy environments. When searching for the higher‑pitched *"ring"*, hold the phone flat and sweep it slowly; turning your head to face the same direction as the phone will give the best spatial audio experience.

The lighthouse metaphor for the beacon’s design suggests a few practical points:

1. There is no *"correct"* direction to travel when using the beacon — with Soundscape you choose how to get there;

2. The higher‑pitched *"ring"* helps you pinpoint the destination’s direction only — it does not tell you how to get there;

3. If you already generally know how to reach your destination, you may prefer to mute the beacon for most of your trip and turn it on only as you get nearer.
